ocean floor.

48:03.740 --> 48:06.400
So have we possibly retrieved the USOs?

48:06.540 --> 48:07.280
I think, yes.

48:07.600 --> 48:09.220
Uh, I believe it's probably a yes.

48:09.480 --> 48:14.600
The Glomar Explorer, yeah, this huge corporation, they actually recovered a, a sunken Soviet submarine

48:14.600 --> 48:16.120
in the 1970s.

48:16.120 --> 48:20.060
And it was an incredible feat because they went down something like three miles down to

48:20.060 --> 48:20.880
the Pacific floor.

48:21.080 --> 48:25.800
They got it, it broke, um, but they, they recovered half of it.

48:25.880 --> 48:29.580
They actually gave a proper military burial to some of the Soviet sailors that they recovered.

48:29.580 --> 48:31.400
So that was an incredible thing.

48:31.400 --> 48:39.680
And, um, in terms of recovering disks, I once, I received a, a communication from a, um, a

48:39.680 --> 48:41.080
gentleman who was former US Navy.

48:41.420 --> 48:47.220
He told me about having attended a conference, uh, not this one, but another, another excellent

48:47.220 --> 48:49.940
one, the International UFO Congress, a really great place there.

48:49.940 --> 48:55.480
And he said, you know, I'm, I'm hanging outside and I run to this other Navy guy between lectures

48:55.480 --> 48:56.220
and we're just chatting.

48:57.160 --> 49:02.040
And this guy was, um, aboard the USS Nautilus submarine.

49:02.160 --> 49:03.640
So that was the first nuclear powered submarine.

49:04.220 --> 49:08.380
And he said, you know, the Nautilus went through a retrofitting or a refitting, excuse me, in the

49:08.380 --> 49:10.360
mid sixties, which is true.

49:10.500 --> 49:11.340
We know about this.

49:11.340 --> 49:16.200
And he said, one thing that, um, that we did is we had like this, we created this hatch,

49:16.320 --> 49:25.540
this side hatch to be able to acquire objects that were, uh, disks, uh, unknown, unknown objects,

49:25.760 --> 49:27.140
um, in the ocean.

49:28.020 --> 49:34.300
Now, I mean, uh, this guy, the guy like wrote to me and then, and then he, he never really

49:34.300 --> 49:35.800
was able to follow up with this Navy guy.

49:35.860 --> 49:36.940
So he lost that whole thread.

49:36.940 --> 49:40.220
So he wrote to me and we went back and forth on it.

49:40.480 --> 49:44.700
And, um, I, I reported that it's in, it's in my first volume here.

49:44.800 --> 49:49.260
I don't know if this is true or not, like, because a Navy submarine is not going to be

49:49.260 --> 49:51.740
able to go down to the ocean, the bottom of the ocean floor.

49:51.800 --> 49:55.960
That is way too deep, but it can, you know, about 10 or 15% of our oceans are basically

49:55.960 --> 49:56.780
ocean shelf.

49:57.840 --> 49:59.560
And that might be a different thing.

49:59.560 --> 50:04.520
And you might be able to, um, have a submarine kind of work, work that area.

50:04.520 --> 50:11.460
You know, if, if this is a true thing, um, definitely look, we have a long, long history.

50:11.580 --> 50:14.700
Crash retrievals is a really strong interest of mine personally.

50:15.280 --> 50:22.140
And there is no question we've had a number of crash retrievals or recoveries of these UAP.

50:22.580 --> 50:24.660
We could do a whole interview on that.

50:24.720 --> 50:26.860
Frankly, there's just a lot to say about that.

50:26.860 --> 50:31.520
And now those are retrievals that we know about from land.

50:32.580 --> 50:38.340
Um, you know, the waters of this world are, are much more remote to us and much more mysterious.

50:38.340 --> 50:40.120
And I don't think a lot of these stories come through.

50:40.680 --> 50:45.960
I did, um, there is one gentleman that, uh, I did speak to many years ago.

50:45.960 --> 50:47.600
His name is David Noble Whitehorse.

50:47.920 --> 50:50.240
And he was, uh, did you want to talk about this?

50:50.360 --> 50:50.760
Yeah, we did.

50:50.820 --> 50:51.240
I thought we did.

50:51.300 --> 50:51.420
Yeah.

50:51.420 --> 50:53.400
So, and did you interview him?

50:53.860 --> 50:57.720
No, but it made its way into the Malmgren thing that I did.

50:57.940 --> 51:03.440
And then I realized it was actually, you know, I think there, yeah, it was a whole can of worms.

51:03.700 --> 51:06.360
But this, I think it was a year before Malmgren.

51:06.400 --> 51:08.100
I think that was actually a little off.

51:08.140 --> 51:11.060
It was one year because it was, it wasn't Bluegill Triple Prime.

51:11.120 --> 51:13.220
I think it was one year before.

51:13.480 --> 51:13.660
Yeah.

51:13.780 --> 51:13.940
Yeah.

51:14.000 --> 51:14.240
62.

51:14.760 --> 51:16.280
And he's a really interesting character.

51:16.440 --> 51:17.440
He's a great guy.

51:17.440 --> 51:22.120
I, you know, I interviewed him, uh, I don't know, 15 years ago and, uh, I can't even remember

51:22.120 --> 51:28.500
how I found him, but we talked extensively and he was a member of, uh, aboard a U.S.

51:28.500 --> 51:30.240
ship called the Finch back in 1962.

51:30.720 --> 51:35.460
They were involved in what became Bluegill Triple Prime, part of what is called Operation

51:35.460 --> 51:36.000
Dominic.

51:36.060 --> 51:36.860
You can look this up.

51:37.500 --> 51:41.280
And, uh, there's a series of high altitude nuclear detonations.

51:41.620 --> 51:45.500
Uh, this is at the peak of like, we were just going crazy detonating these hydrogen, massive

51:45.500 --> 51:46.360
hydrogen bombs.

51:46.800 --> 51:47.480
It was crazy.

51:48.020 --> 51:51.800
So he said it was, uh, October, this is like right around the time of the Cuban missile

51:51.800 --> 51:55.000
crisis, October 25th, 1962.

51:56.000 --> 52:01.280
They were off a little place called Johnston Island, which is about 500 miles off of Hawaii

52:01.280 --> 52:02.360
out in the Pacific.

52:02.720 --> 52:04.760
And he said, we did a detonation.

52:05.760 --> 52:09.380
He said, we often would have bogeys in the atmosphere before we would do a detonation.

52:09.380 --> 52:11.280
Like, that is UFOs.

52:11.400 --> 52:15.720
And they would always disappear just before we would detonate the bomb.

52:16.300 --> 52:18.880
So they're hanging out, checking it out, evidently.

52:19.200 --> 52:23.940
He said on this occasion, so, uh, we, we had to do the debt, the detonation and we were all

52:23.940 --> 52:24.920
ordered below deck.

52:25.200 --> 52:25.900
This is protocol.

52:26.680 --> 52:33.380
And then to his surprise, um, some of the officer or some other guy comes down and says,

52:33.380 --> 52:39.160
you, you, you, and you, and you, I want you out now, uh, out on the, I think the port side,

52:39.280 --> 52:39.860
one of the sides.

52:40.060 --> 52:42.960
He says, you are now to face forward.

52:43.140 --> 52:44.420
You are not to look to the left.

52:44.500 --> 52:45.340
You are not to look to the right.

52:45.500 --> 52:47.400
Just look ahead of you and observe.

52:47.900 --> 52:49.140
And they're like, oh, okay, whatever.

52:49.280 --> 52:49.880
Orders are orders.

52:50.340 --> 52:58.420
And so a, what they see is this long cigar shaped object zooming by horizontally.

52:58.420 --> 53:01.020
And that's all he saw.

53:01.920 --> 53:04.300
Then he was doing a cross train with radar.

53:05.020 --> 53:09.540
So later that day or evening, he's talking to the radar guys and they're all talking about

53:09.540 --> 53:12.540
the bogey that was, seemed to be shot out of the sky.

53:13.160 --> 53:15.220
And, and this is clearly what he saw.

53:15.360 --> 53:21.040
And it landed, uh, at some point in the Pacific and they were sending a series of ships to go

53:21.040 --> 53:22.760
and see about trying to recover it.

53:23.980 --> 53:24.420
Fascinating.

53:24.680 --> 53:28.040
So actually I, I, I did a little research.

53:28.040 --> 53:31.420
I think the Finch might've been an earlier operation, Dominic test.

53:31.540 --> 53:33.220
We can workshop this live or I don't know.

53:33.300 --> 53:38.320
Anybody could search, but, um, there's, I have a lot of reason to believe that there

53:38.320 --> 53:41.740
were anomalous objects that came out.

53:41.920 --> 53:46.160
Actually Bob Jacobs, 1964, uh, you know, Vandenberg case.

53:46.320 --> 53:52.060
He was stationed at Johnston at all a few months before the Vandenberg case where he saw, he was

53:52.060 --> 53:53.760
a photo instrumentation specialist.

53:53.760 --> 53:57.980
He was on big Sur and he saw a UFO wraparound Atlas 8F missile.

53:57.980 --> 53:58.220
That's right.

53:58.340 --> 53:58.700
That's right.

53:58.940 --> 54:00.320
And only two years apart.

54:00.640 --> 54:08.040
And he said it was, you know, ubiquitous water cooler conversation that a UFO shoot down was

54:08.040 --> 54:12.380
being used as a cover for shooting down a Soviet nuke.

54:12.380 --> 54:17.760
The scuttlebutt at the time, by every single person on that Island, when I got there, this

54:17.760 --> 54:22.060
was engineers, technicians, um, my airmen who had been down there before me.

54:22.060 --> 54:29.600
Um, we were told that what happened is the, the Soviets had launched a nuke into orbit

54:29.600 --> 54:34.780
up above us and JFK told Khrushchev, take that down.

54:34.780 --> 54:40.740
So I found that to be an extremely interesting, uh, another firsthand testimony.

54:40.900 --> 54:41.420
That's wacky.

54:41.500 --> 54:42.900
And this was around Bluegill triple prime.

54:42.980 --> 54:46.840
So this was, that was, you know, what this detonation that had happened a year earlier.

54:46.840 --> 54:49.840
And then you have the whole Malmgren testimony, which I think is very important as well.

54:50.340 --> 54:54.980
Um, I want to ask you, so this begets all sorts of questions around secrecy.

54:55.220 --> 54:57.040
You know, everybody talks about the air force.

54:57.160 --> 55:03.540
You have, uh, in 1947, uh, uh, Twining writing this memo, you know, he's the head of air material

55:03.540 --> 55:04.640
command for the air force.

55:05.120 --> 55:12.080
Uh, and he's expressing kind of earnest confusion as to how UFO, how UFOs work, but he says they're,

55:12.080 --> 55:15.120
they're, you know, uh, real and not visionary or fictitious.

55:15.520 --> 55:21.960
The office of Naval intelligence is the oldest, uh, uh, Intel, uh, organization in the U S you

55:21.960 --> 55:23.020
know, 1890s.

55:23.440 --> 55:26.120
Um, you know, they call it the silent service, the Navy.

55:26.740 --> 55:31.560
Um, what does the Navy know and how deeply embedded are they in this issue?

55:31.560 --> 55:36.920
Even the reports that came out, I think in 2020, 20 and 2021 were office of Naval intelligence

55:36.920 --> 55:37.320
led.

55:37.660 --> 55:37.760
Yeah.

55:38.120 --> 55:38.280
Yeah.

55:38.380 --> 55:41.220
Navy, I think has been deeply, deeply involved in this from the beginning.

55:41.220 --> 55:46.840
It took me a long time, even, you know, researching this for years to fully appreciate just how

55:46.840 --> 55:48.440
deep their involvement was.

55:48.600 --> 55:52.620
If you go back and look at some of the original, uh, books that were published by people like

55:52.620 --> 55:55.560
Donald Kehoe, he's one of the people that kind of was my springboard.

55:55.780 --> 55:57.620
Uh, he kind of talks a lot about this.

55:57.620 --> 56:01.640
Uh, Kehoe was a Marine, so associated with the Navy.

56:02.440 --> 56:05.360
And so he knew a lot of top Navy brass.

56:05.680 --> 56:06.920
He was friends with many admirals.

56:07.600 --> 56:12.740
And, uh, so he had a real ear to what was going on there and described quite frequently

56:12.740 --> 56:15.420
the rivalry between the Navy and the Air Force.

56:15.520 --> 56:16.480
This is very well known.

56:16.620 --> 56:20.820
I mean, after the second world war, the Air Force was the new organization.

56:21.060 --> 56:22.040
They had a lot of prestige.

56:22.040 --> 56:26.160
They were the only, uh, uh, branch that had nuclear weapons.

56:26.320 --> 56:27.540
The Navy wanted their own nukes.

56:27.620 --> 56:28.440
They eventually got it.

56:28.760 --> 56:33.040
There was something around 1949 or so called the revolt of the admirals.

56:33.140 --> 56:37.800
This was a big political, uh, fight between the Navy and the Air Force.

56:37.900 --> 56:41.660
So there's all, there was all this kind of bureaucratic institutional rivalry that already

56:41.660 --> 56:42.100
existed.

56:42.100 --> 56:47.120
But it happened, it also had to do with this, the flying saucers, as they were being called

56:47.120 --> 56:47.560
back then.

56:47.900 --> 56:49.840
Uh, the Air Force was getting all the attention.

56:50.520 --> 56:56.560
But one thing that Kehoe wrote about, even back then, was, like, Navy people were having

56:56.560 --> 56:57.320
UFO encounters.

56:57.580 --> 57:04.080
And the Navy personnel would get really angry because, uh, Air Force people would come on

57:04.080 --> 57:07.600
the Navy ships and throw their weight around and take over the investigations.

57:07.600 --> 57:09.660
And the Navy guys were really resentful of this.

57:10.220 --> 57:14.140
The Secretary of the Navy in 1950 was a guy named Dan Kimball.

57:14.860 --> 57:16.380
He had his own UFO sighting.

57:16.940 --> 57:21.780
So he was, he was flying in duel, uh, with, uh, Admiral Arthur Radford, who's quite famous.

57:22.240 --> 57:25.860
They were flying out from California to Hawaii, uh, in 1950.

57:26.080 --> 57:26.920
I think it was 1950.

57:27.880 --> 57:28.160
Yes.

57:28.160 --> 57:31.440
And, uh, Kehoe wrote about this.

57:31.840 --> 57:37.340
So what happened was, Kimball's plane and Radford's plane were both accosted by an object

57:37.340 --> 57:39.180
that circled around their aircraft.

57:40.140 --> 57:41.800
They were, like, a number of miles apart.

57:42.020 --> 57:43.820
But they both had this happen.

57:44.700 --> 57:51.140
And as a result, Kimball decided, we are going to have our own separate investigation of this.

57:51.200 --> 57:52.020
The hell with the Air Force.

57:52.920 --> 57:56.700
But, uh, at least according to what Kehoe learned, it didn't seem to take off.

57:57.000 --> 57:57.800
It didn't really go anywhere.

57:58.160 --> 58:00.120
But their, the rivalry was always there.

58:00.460 --> 58:03.240
I think Ross Colthart is, is somewhere here.

58:03.240 --> 58:08.280
And he ended up having a conversation with Nat Kobitz, who is Director of Science and Technology

58:08.280 --> 58:09.720
for the Navy.

58:10.460 --> 58:12.820
And, um, this is the end of Nat's life.

58:12.880 --> 58:14.000
I think he was dying of cancer.

58:14.100 --> 58:19.680
And he said that he had seen UFO technology at Wright-Patterson Air Force Base.

58:19.840 --> 58:24.740
And it was involved these sort of, you know, um, bonded metals that were fabricated at the

58:24.740 --> 58:27.260
atomic level and said all sorts of other interesting stuff.

58:27.260 --> 58:28.840
So, yeah, I've, I've heard about this.

58:28.920 --> 58:30.460
I've not actually listened to it yet.

58:30.460 --> 58:32.540
And I'm, I'm kind of really excited about doing that.

58:34.540 --> 58:39.240
General Eisenhower is called back to duty, meeting Defense Secretary James Forrestal to

58:39.240 --> 58:40.700
discuss many vital questions.

58:40.700 --> 58:47.000
So, uh, one other kind of interesting axis around that time, Navy, uh, James Forrestal.

58:47.120 --> 58:51.140
So, James Forrestal was the Secretary of Navy before becoming, uh, Secretary of Defense,

58:51.260 --> 58:53.800
meeting a very mysterious, untimely death.

58:53.820 --> 58:54.300
He was murdered.

58:54.740 --> 58:55.220
Okay.

58:55.660 --> 58:56.360
Let's hear that.

58:56.420 --> 58:57.640
He was absolutely murdered.

58:57.640 --> 58:59.420
Did he have anything to do with the UFO issue?

58:59.420 --> 58:59.660
Maybe.

58:59.780 --> 59:00.360
Yeah, probably.

59:00.520 --> 59:00.800
Okay.

59:01.040 --> 59:01.440
Probably.

59:01.980 --> 59:02.340
Yeah.

59:02.440 --> 59:07.780
So, uh, Forrestal, this was one of my real pet projects when I broke into this field.

59:08.600 --> 59:12.300
And, uh, Forrestal was a fascinating, very brilliant man.

59:12.300 --> 59:14.860
Of course, uh, kind of a financial wizard.

59:14.860 --> 59:19.620
Uh, I think he played football at Princeton back in, you know, as an undergraduate.

59:19.620 --> 59:26.720
Just, so then he becomes, um, after he makes his fortune, he becomes one of those so-called

59:26.720 --> 59:31.300
dollar a year men, uh, under FDR for the war, basically to support the war effort.

59:31.380 --> 59:35.100
He becomes undersecretary of the Navy and then secretary of the Navy at the end of the

59:35.100 --> 59:35.340
war.

59:35.340 --> 59:43.360
And he, um, he was actually one of these guys who fought against a strong secretary

59:43.360 --> 59:44.660
of defense position.

59:44.940 --> 59:50.200
When, when, um, we were going through the reorganization in 1947, National Security Act,

59:50.840 --> 59:54.000
uh, kind of a total, let's like, we're done with the Republic.

59:54.140 --> 59:55.580
We're creating the empire now, people.

59:55.660 --> 59:57.560
And we got to reorganize the whole military system.

59:58.900 --> 01:00:05.180
Forrestal fought tenaciously for naval independence under a unified secretary.

01:00:05.180 --> 01:00:11.680
And, and the real issue was, does the SecDef have budgetary authority over the independent

01:00:11.680 --> 01:00:12.260
services?

01:00:12.760 --> 01:00:14.160
That was, that's really where the power is.

01:00:14.940 --> 01:00:21.240
And, and, and Forrestal particularly fought so well that he won that battle and the secretary

01:00:21.240 --> 01:00:28.500
of defense, uh, originally did not have the authority to tell the army and the Navy and

01:00:28.500 --> 01:00:30.540
the air force what their budget would be.

01:00:31.280 --> 01:00:32.580
He didn't have that capability.

01:00:32.580 --> 01:00:33.880
So he was a weak SecDef.

01:00:34.240 --> 01:00:39.040
And then irony of ironies, Forrestal ends up in that position as secretary of defense.

01:00:39.160 --> 01:00:46.560
So he, uh, for his entire two and a half year tenure in that role, one of the biggest problems

01:00:46.560 --> 01:00:51.680
he had with Truman, we tend to forget this, was that the, uh, that Truman wanted to cut

01:00:51.680 --> 01:00:53.960
the military budget significantly.

01:00:53.960 --> 01:00:58.340
At the same time, he wanted to expand U.S. military presence globally.

01:00:58.900 --> 01:01:00.020
So it's kind of a disconnect there.

01:01:00.640 --> 01:01:06.900
And the, uh, the joint chiefs were saying like, $15 billion a year out of your mind, which of

01:01:06.900 --> 01:01:07.720
course that's nothing today.

01:01:07.800 --> 01:01:10.120
But at the time it was also not very much.

01:01:10.200 --> 01:01:11.820
They wanted like 30 billion, I think.

01:01:12.620 --> 01:01:17.720
And Forrestal sided with them, but he was kind of stuck because Truman's just like, just make

01:01:17.720 --> 01:01:18.200
it happen.

01:01:18.200 --> 01:01:22.020
And so they had a very unhappy relationship over that.

01:01:22.620 --> 01:01:31.480
Then at the same time, we have the flying saucers making their appearance in, in the military

01:01:31.480 --> 01:01:33.920
world and in the American psyche.

01:01:33.920 --> 01:01:35.720
It's like we're talking about it.

01:01:36.200 --> 01:01:40.780
And this was something that he was definitely very aware of.

01:01:41.200 --> 01:01:42.760
It was impossible not to be.

01:01:42.760 --> 01:01:48.400
Um, I read Forrestal's published two volume diaries, uh, which were published after his

01:01:48.400 --> 01:01:48.600
death.

01:01:48.660 --> 01:01:49.760
We'll get to his death in a second.

01:01:49.980 --> 01:01:54.320
And of course, there's not a, not a mention of, of UFOs or flying saucers in there.

01:01:54.940 --> 01:01:56.760
But anyway, so what, what ended up happening?

01:01:56.860 --> 01:01:59.820
So, uh, Forrestal and Truman, their relationship became rocky.

01:02:00.460 --> 01:02:02.320
Truman's up for reelection in 1948.

01:02:02.740 --> 01:02:04.960
Everyone's like, sure, he's going to lose.

01:02:05.060 --> 01:02:07.800
Thomas Dewey, the Republicans, sure, win.

01:02:07.800 --> 01:02:16.200
And, and, and Forrestal, bad move, had met with Dewey and it got out and Truman was pissed

01:02:16.200 --> 01:02:17.920
and like, you betrayed me.

01:02:18.840 --> 01:02:26.740
Uh, but anyway, so Truman wins, shocks the world, tells Forrestal shortly after that, you're

01:02:26.740 --> 01:02:27.120
done.

01:02:27.480 --> 01:02:31.620
I think in January 49, he says, you're out, you're out.

01:02:31.620 --> 01:02:37.800
And they give, but you know, publicly they give Forrestal this nice, uh, going away ceremony.

01:02:37.800 --> 01:02:39.860
It's like, you're a great American and all this stuff.

01:02:39.980 --> 01:02:41.520
And this is the crazy thing.

01:02:41.520 --> 01:02:48.800
So for, it's January 49, Forrestal leaves this ceremony and gets into a limousine.

01:02:48.940 --> 01:02:53.940
And in the limousine is the secretary of the air force, Stuart Symington.

01:02:54.380 --> 01:02:58.520
Now Symington was like one of Forrestal's major political enemies.

01:02:58.520 --> 01:03:03.080
Forrestal was convinced, and I bet he was right, that he was being followed.

01:03:03.980 --> 01:03:05.860
Uh, Symington was probably involved.

01:03:05.960 --> 01:03:11.000
There was a journalist back then named Drew Pearson who was writing stories about Forrestal.

01:03:11.100 --> 01:03:16.780
And people were noticing all throughout this time that Forrestal seemed like he was unraveling.

01:03:17.140 --> 01:03:20.060
He started developing these weird, nervous tics.

01:03:20.660 --> 01:03:24.560
He said, I'm being followed by strange, foreign looking men.

01:03:24.620 --> 01:03:25.220
He's looking around.

01:03:25.260 --> 01:03:25.920
He's very paranoid.

01:03:25.920 --> 01:03:31.640
He started, uh, dipping his fingers into glasses of water all the time and just wetting his lips.

01:03:31.840 --> 01:03:34.160
Like there's some weird thing going on with him.

01:03:34.800 --> 01:03:41.760
So, um, so he gets out of this meeting and he goes into the limo and there's Stuart Symington, who they hate each other.

01:03:42.460 --> 01:03:48.740
And all that we know is that Symington said this, I want to talk to you about something.

01:03:48.740 --> 01:03:53.400
No one, to my knowledge, knows what actually happened on the limo ride back.

